Reference - Authors: Hanni Höhn; Cornelius Kortsik; Glenn Tully; Katja Nilges; Antje Necker; Kirsten Freitag; Claudia Neukirch; Peter Galle; Hans Löhr; Markus J Maeurer
Reference - Title: Longitudinal analysis of Mycobacterium tuberculosis 19-kDa antigen-specific T cells in patients with pulmonary tuberculosis: association with disease activity and cross-reactivity to a peptide from HIVenv gp120.
1st immunogen - Name: Mycobacterium tuberculosis
Assay - Comments: SIV gp120  tetramer-sorted cells from patients with pulmonary tuberculosis were used in a cross-recognition study comparing activation of T-cellsinduced by mimotope from M. tuberculosis, HIV gp120, and SIV gp120.  Results for this epitope were (cytokine/patients):  GM-CSF 3/3, IL-4 0/3, IFN-γ 3/3.  Results were similar for SIV gp 120.  M. tuberculosis mimotope-induced activation is distinguished in that it elicits lower levels of IFN-γ release but does elicit robust IL-4 release.

Reference - Authors: C Brander; G Corradin; T Hasler; W J Pichler
Reference - Title: Peptide immunization in humans: a combined CD8+/CD4+ T cell-targeted vaccine restimulates the memory CD4 T cell response but fails to induce cytotoxic T lymphocytes (CTL).
Epitope - Epitope Comments: The following refers to the epitope id as found in the original FIMM database: P001183.
1st immunogen - Name: Tetanus toxin
Immunization - Comments: The carrier was composed of p30, FNNFTVSFWLRVPKVSASHLE.
Assay - Comments: Killing of epitope-pulsed-targets was measured. Data originally imported from the Database of Functional Molecular Immunology, FIMM (http://sdmc.lit.org.sg:8080/fimm/).

Reference - Authors: J Sutton; S Rowland-Jones; W Rosenberg; D Nixon; F Gotch; X M Gao; N Murray; A Spoonas; P Driscoll; M Smith
Reference - Title: A sequence pattern for peptides presented to cytotoxic T lymphocytes by HLA B8 revealed by analysis of epitopes and eluted peptides.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: The GAG 24-32 sequence is identical in many HIV-1 isolates.
1st in vivo Process - Process Type: Exposure with existing immune reactivity without evidence for disease
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
in vitro immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: The CTL donor was seropsitive for HIV-1.  HIV-1-specific CTL were generated from an HIV-1 seropositive patient by culturing PBMC. The details of restimulation were not given.
Assay - Comments: HIV-1-specific CTL were generated from PBMC and tested for lytic activity against different truncated peptides within the p17.3 duodecamer epitope from the HIV-1 GAG protein. GAG 24-32 (p17.3a) was determined to be the optimal epitope. Data originally imported from the HLA Ligand Database (http://hlaligand.ouhsc.edu/).

Reference - Authors: T K Hoffmann; V S Donnenberg; U Friebe-Hoffmann; E M Meyer; C R Rinaldo; A B DeLeo; T L Whiteside; A D Donnenberg
Reference - Title: Competition of peptide-MHC class I tetrameric complexes with anti-CD3 provides evidence for specificity of peptide binding to the TCR complex.
Assay - Comments: The number of epitope specific CD8+ cells out of the CD8+ population present in healthy donor PBMC was found to be 1/6,067. The majority of tetramer positive cells were CD45RO-/CD45RAbright. In order to confirm tetramer specificity for the TCR, competition experiments studying tetramer binding and subsequent staining with anti-CD3 were performed. The degree of tetramer/anti-CD3 competition did not correlate with the intensity or fequency of epitope specific tetramer staining, however, competition did correlate in experiments using an infuenza matrix epitope (M 58-66) for which donors had presumed exposure.

Reference - Authors: Stefan Kostense; Sigrid A Otto; Gerlinde J Knol; Erik H Manting; Nening M Nanlohy; Christine Jansen; Joep M A Lange; Marinus H J van Oers; Frank Miedema; Debbie van Baarle
Reference - Title: Functional restoration of human immunodeficiency virus and Epstein-Barr virus-specific CD8(+) T cells during highly active antiretroviral therapy is associated with an increase in CD4(+) T cells.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: Data originally imported from the HLA Ligand Database (http://hlaligand.ouhsc.edu/).
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: The subjects were HIV-positive males undergoing highly active anti-retroviral therapy (HAART); pre- and post-treatment samples were obtained.
Assay - Comments: Epitope-specific CD8+ T cells were detected in PBMCs of two HIV positive individuals. However, the cells numbers differed between donors and was dependent upon whether they responded to highly active anti-retroviral therapy (HAART).

Reference - Authors: L Dorrell; C A O'Callaghan; W Britton; S Hambleton; A McMichael; G L Smith; S Rowland-Jones; T J Blanchard
Reference - Title: Recombinant modified vaccinia virus Ankara efficiently restimulates human cytotoxic T lymphocytes in vitro.
1st in vivo Process - Process Type: Exposure with existing immune reactivity without evidence for disease
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: Although donors were HIV-1 seropositive, the in vitro immunizing antigen is a recombinant vaccinia virus (Ankara strain) expressing the HIV-1 gag protein (MVA-gag).  PBMC were cultured with a sonicated preparation of recombinant vaccina virus (Ankara strain) expressing the HIV-1 gag protein (MVA-gag) at a multiplicity of infection (MOI) of 0.1. Cultures were supplemented with 10 U/mL of recombinant human IL-2 on day 3 and tested for lytic activity against target cells on day 10 and day 14.
Assay - Comments: HIV-1 gag-specific CTL were expanded in vitro by restimulating PBMC with a recombinant vaccinia virus (Ankara) encoding the HIV-1 gag protein (MVA-gag). After 10-14 days in culture, CTL were tested for lytic activity against B-lymphoblastoid cell lines (BCL) pulsed with the gag180-188 peptide.

Reference - Authors: A Lalvani; T Dong; G Ogg; A A Patham; H Newell; A V Hill; A J McMichael; S Rowland-Jones
Reference - Title: Optimization of a peptide-based protocol employing IL-7 for in vitro restimulation of human cytotoxic T lymphocyte precursors.
Immunization - Comments: CTL were generated through in vitro restimulation of PBMC with the epitope, IL-2, and IL-7.
Assay - Comments: CTL derived from HIV negative donors through in vitro restimulation with the epitope were unable to lyse B-LCL presenting the epitope, despite the addition of IL-7 in the initial cultures used to generate the CTL lines. However, CTL generated from HIV+ donors were able to recognize the epitope.

Reference - Authors: A Lalvani; T Dong; G Ogg; A A Patham; H Newell; A V Hill; A J McMichael; S Rowland-Jones
Reference - Title: Optimization of a peptide-based protocol employing IL-7 for in vitro restimulation of human cytotoxic T lymphocyte precursors.
1st in vivo Process - Process Type: Exposure with existing immune reactivity without evidence for disease
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: CTL were generated through in vitro restimulation of PBMC with the epitope and IL-2. In some cases, IL-7 was also added to the CTL culture.
Assay - Comments: CTL derived from HIV+ donors through in vitro restimulation with the epitope were able to lyse B-LCL presenting the epitope when IL-7 was included in the initial cultures used to generate the CTL lines. The use of 20ng/ml of IL-7 resulted in the highest increase in epitope specific lysis with the least increase in nonspecific CTL activity.

Reference - Authors: A Lalvani; T Dong; G Ogg; A A Patham; H Newell; A V Hill; A J McMichael; S Rowland-Jones
Reference - Title: Optimization of a peptide-based protocol employing IL-7 for in vitro restimulation of human cytotoxic T lymphocyte precursors.
1st in vivo Process - Process Type: Exposure with existing immune reactivity without evidence for disease
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: CTL were generated through in vitro restimulation of PBMC with the epitope and IL-2. In some cases, IL-7 was also added to the CTL culture.
Assay - Comments: CTL derived from HIV+ donors through in vitro restimulation with the epitope bound tetramers presenting the epitope. The numbers of epitope specific CD8+ cells increased with the addition of IL-7 in the initial cultures used to generate the CTL lines. The use of 20ng/ml of IL-7 resulted in the highest increase in epitope specific lysis with the least increase in nonspecific CTL activity, while the use of 40ng/ml of IL-7 resulted in the greatest increase in epitope specific cells by tetramer analysis.

Reference - Authors: J Alexander; C Oseroff; J Sidney; P Wentworth; E Keogh; G Hermanson; F V Chisari; R T Kubo; H M Grey; A Sette
Reference - Title: Derivation of HLA-A11/Kb transgenic mice: functional CTL repertoire and recognition of human A11-restricted CTL epitopes.
1st immunogen - Name: TVQPIVLPEK
Immunization - Comments: HLA-A11/Kb mice were immunized by injection of 50ug of HLA-A11 binding-peptide mixed with 140ug of helper IAb-restircted epitope p128-140 of hepatitis B core antigen in PBS/10% DMSO emulsified in incomplete Freund's adjuvant.  At day 11 post-immunization, splenocytes were isolated.  At day 11 post-immunization, splenocytes were isolated and stimulated with 1ug/ml of peptide in the presence or absence of syngeneic irradiated LPS blasts for 6 days.
Assay - Comments: CTLs from mice immunized with HIV pol peptide p419-428 were tested for their ability to recognize and lyse peptide-pulsed targets. CTLs from 2 of the 9 immunized mice were capable of peptide-specific lysis.

Reference - Authors: S Huet; D F Nixon; J B Rothbard; A Townsend; S A Ellis; A J McMichael
Reference - Title: Structural homologies between two HLA B27-restricted peptides suggest residues important for interaction with HLA B27.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: No strain was specified, so a representative Swiss-Prot entry with matching sequence was chosen.
1st in vivo Process - Process Type: Exposure with existing immune reactivity without evidence for disease
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: The donor was HIV-seropositive.  Lymphocytes were stimulated with autologous PHA-activated lymphocytes. At day 7, cells were restimulated with an irradiated B cell line preincubated with gag265-279 peptide.
Assay - Comments: The positively charged N-terminal Lys of gag265-276 (KRWIILGLNKIV) is essential for binding to HLA-B27 because its removal eliminated recognition by HIV-specific CTL in a lysis assay. When the tryptophan at position 3 is replaced by leucine or tyrosine, the modified peptides were not recognized by HIV-specific CTL suggesting that the tryptophan may interact with the T cell receptor, since MHC binding was actually enhanced.

Immunization - Comments: An epitope specific CD4+ T cell line was generated from CD8 depleted PBMC of HIV+ patients through in vitro restimulation with the epitope and IL-2.
Assay - Comments: An epitope specific CD4+ T cell line produced IFNg in response to the epitope.

Reference - Authors: Thomas J Scriba; Marco Purbhoo; Cheryl L Day; Nicola Robinson; Sarah Fidler; Julie Fox; Jonathan N Weber; Paul Klenerman; Andrew K Sewell; Rodney E Phillips
Reference - Title: Ultrasensitive detection and phenotyping of CD4+ T cells with optimized HLA class II tetramer staining.
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: An epitope specific CD4+ T cell line and clone were generated from CD8 depleted PBMC of HIV+ patients through in vitro restimulation with the epitope and IL-2.
Assay - Comments: Epitope specific tetramers bound an epitope specific CD4+ T cell line and clone. The staining was demonstrated to be rapid, to not require internalization, and was able to identify epitope specific cells within a mixed population of PBMC. CD4+ enrichment enhanced the identification of epitope specific cells within PBMC from patients with a low frequency of epitope specific cells.

Assay - Comments: Epitope specific CD4+ T cells were identified in CD8 depleted PBMC from HIV+ patients, which were undetectable prior to depletion. The tetramer positive cells were shown to be CD28+, CD27+, and CCR7lo.

Reference - Authors: S Uno-Furuta; S Tamaki; Y Takebe; S Takamura; A Kamei; G Kim; I Kuromatsu; M Kaito; Y Adachi; Y Yasutomi
Reference - Title: Induction of virus-specific cytotoxic T lymphocytes by in vivo electric administration of peptides.
1st immunogen - Name: RIQRGPGRAFVTIGK
Immunization - Comments: Mice were injected with the 50 ug of peptide with plasmid and then the site of inoculation was immediately given an electric pulse by an Electric Square Porator. Mice were injected with the 50 ug of peptide and then the site of inoculation was immediately given an electric pulse by an Electric Square Porator.
Assay - Comments: Spleen cells obtained from peptide plus plasmid DNA-immunized mice were assessed for their ability to lyse peptide-pulsed MHC-matched target cells. Two separate plasmids were administered individually with peptide, plasmid pCMV-LacZ which is known to contain potent immunostimulatory sequence, or plasmid DNA having murine B7-1 cDNA. In either case, immunization was followed by electric pulses. Both formulations were found to enhance peptide-specific cytotoxicity compared to peptide immunization/electric pulsing alone. Spleen cells obtained from peptide-immunized mice were assessed for their ability to lyse peptide-pulsed MHC-matched target cells. Effector cells were elicited in mice immunized with peptide followed by electric pulse administration, however, no such effector cells were developed in mice immunized with the same peptides without in vivo electric administration or unimmunized control mice.

Reference - Authors: G R Leggatt; A Hosmalin; C D Pendleton; A Kumar; S Hoffman; J A Berzofsky
Reference - Title: The importance of pairwise interactions between peptide residues in the delineation of TCR specificity.
1st immunogen - Name: reverse transcriptase
Immunization - Comments: The details of the generation of Pol alpha CTL cell line was from the cited reference: Hosmalin, A. et al. 1990. Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA 87:2344. [PMID: 1690429].
Assay - Comments: The epitope was deduced to be minimal peptide required for sensitizing targets to lysis by pol alpha CTLs. Alanine substitutions analysis suggested that positions Glu2, Met3, Glu4, Glu6, Lys8 and Ile9 were critical for recognition. Alanine substitution of Lys5 had no effect whereas Glu6 was critical, but double substitution at positions 5 and 6 restored recognition.

Reference - Authors: E A Duarte; G Eberl; G Corradin
Reference - Title: Specific tolerization of active cytolytic T lymphocyte responses in vivo with soluble peptides.
1st immunogen - Name: MYAPPIGGQI
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: One dose of 4ug
Immunization - Comments: Mice were first immunized with IFA followed by immunization with a MAP construct containing 2 T helper epitopes from tetanus toxin, P2 and P30, the epitope, and a P. berghei circumsporozoite protein epitope, residues 252-260.  CTL were generated through in vitro restimulation with the epitope and the P. berghei circumsporozoite epitope.
Assay - Comments: CTL from mice immunized with the epitope lysed target cells presenting the epitope. Additional immunization with the epitope 3 days after the epitope was first administered resulted in tolerization and lack of response to the epitope. By 15 days after tolerization, the CTL response had recovered, but could be retolerized through additional administration of the epitope. Suppressor activity was not detected in the spleens of tolerized animals.

Reference - Authors: Jeff Alexander; Carla Oseroff; John Sidney; Alessandro Sette
Reference - Title: Derivation of HLA-B*0702 transgenic mice: functional CTL repertoire and recognition of human B*0702-restricted CTL epitopes.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: The epitope was imported from the TopBank database and recurated.
1st immunogen - Name: FPVRPQVPL
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 1 dose of 50 µg
Immunization - Comments: Mice were immunized at the base of the tail with 50 µg epitope and 140 µg of a helper epitope (HBVc 128-140; TPPAYRPPNAPIL). Spleens were removed 11 days later and splenocytes were subjected to two rounds of in vitro stimulation for 6 days with epitope and irradiated LPS-activated spleen cells as APCs.
Assay - Comments: Splenocytes from immunized mice that were subjected to two in vitro restimulations with the epitope produced IFN-γ in response to the epitope presented by Jurkat cells transfected with a B*0702/Kb chimeric gene. CD8+ T cells assayed ex vivo 11 days post-immunization without restimulation did not produce significant IFN-γ in response to the epitope.

Reference - Title: Derivation of HLA-B*0702 transgenic mice: functional CTL repertoire and recognition of human B*0702-restricted CTL epitopes.
1st immunogen - Name: VLAEAMSQV
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 1 dose of 100 µg DNA
Immunization - Comments: Mice were pretreated with by injecting cardiotoxin bilaterally into each tibialis anterior muscle. Five days later, mice were immunized with 100 µg EpiGene DNA construct containing 21 HIV epitopes and the PADRE helper epitope. Spleens were removed 11 days later and splenocytes were stimulated in vitro for 6 days with epitope and irradiated LPS-activated spleen cells as APCs. Mice were immunized at the base of the tail with 50 µg epitope and 140 µg of a helper epitope (HBVc 128-140; TPPAYRPPNAPIL). Spleens were removed 11 days later and splenocytes were stimulated in vitro for 6 days with epitope and irradiated LPS-activated spleen cells as APCs.
Assay - Comments: Splenocytes from immunized mice that were subjected to one in vitro restimulation with the epitope produced IFN-γ in response to the epitope presented by Jurkat cells transfected with a A*0201/Kb chimeric gene.

Reference - Authors: Jeff Alexander; Carla Oseroff; John Sidney; Alessandro Sette
Reference - Title: Derivation of HLA-B*0702 transgenic mice: functional CTL repertoire and recognition of human B*0702-restricted CTL epitopes.
1st immunogen - Name: gag polyprotein
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 1 dose of 100 µg DNA
Immunization - Comments: Mice were pretreated with by injecting cardiotoxin bilaterally into each tibialis anterior muscle. Five days later, mice were immunized with 100 µg HIV gag gene DNA. Spleens were removed 11 days later and splenocytes were stimulated in vitro for 6 days with epitope and irradiated LPS-activated spleen cells as APCs.
Assay - Comments: Splenocytes from immunized mice that were subjected to one in vitro restimulation with the epitope did not produce IFN-γ in response to the epitope presented by Jurkat cells transfected with a A*0201/Kb chimeric gene. The results indicate that the epitope was not naturally processed from the antigen for presentation.

Reference - Title: Utilization of MHC class I transgenic mice for development of minigene DNA vaccines encoding multiple HLA-restricted CTL epitopes.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: The epitope sequence was imported from the TopBank database and updated in the IEDB.
1st immunogen - Name: ILKEPVHGV
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 1 dose of 50 µg
Immunization - Comments: Mice were immunized at the base of the tail with the epitope and 140 µg  Th epitope, HBV Core 128-140 (TPPAYRPPNAPIL). Spleens were removed 11 to 14 days after immunization and splenocytes were restimulated in vitro with the epitope.

Reference - Authors: G Y Ishioka; J Fikes; G Hermanson; B Livingston; C Crimi; M Qin; M F del Guercio; C Oseroff; C Dahlberg; J Alexander; R W Chesnut; A Sette
Reference - Title: Utilization of MHC class I transgenic mice for development of minigene DNA vaccines encoding multiple HLA-restricted CTL epitopes.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: The epitope sequence was imported from the TopBank database and updated in the IEDB.
1st immunogen - Name: ILKEPVHGV
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 1 dose of 100 µg DNA
Immunization - Comments: Mice were pretreated with cardiotoxin 4 to 5 days before immunization with plasmid pMin.1 DNA, containing the epitope and 8 other CTL epitopes, a signal sequence and a Th cell PADRE epitope. Spleens were removed 11 to 14 days after immunization and splenocytes were restimulated in vitro twice with the epitope. In separate experiments, mice were boosted with 100 µg pMin.1 DNA at 8 weeks and splenocytes were taken at 18 weeks and stimulated in vitro with epitope. Splenocytes from mice receiving a single immunization were also taken at 18 weeks  for comparison of the memory response. In separate experiments, mice were immunized with pMin.1 DNA with the Th cell PADRE peptide or the signal sequence deleted or the order of the epitopes switched.
Assay - Location of Assay Data in Refere: Figures 2, 4, 6 and Tables II and III
Assay - Comments: CTL from mice immunized with pMin.1 DNA lysed Jurkat A2.1/Kb target cells in the presence of the epitope. Epitope specific CTL lines also lysed Jurkat A2.1/Kb target cells transfected with the pMin.1 construct, indicating the epitope was efficiently processed from the minigene polypeptide. CTL showed a strong memory response to the epitope 18 weeks after the primary immunization. Boosting did not significantly increase this response. Deletion of the signal sequence from the pMin.1 DNA immunogen reduced the response to the epitope, whereas deletion of the Th cell PADRE peptide did not have a significant effect.

Reference - Authors: G Y Ishioka; J Fikes; G Hermanson; B Livingston; C Crimi; M Qin; M F del Guercio; C Oseroff; C Dahlberg; J Alexander; R W Chesnut; A Sette
Reference - Title: Utilization of MHC class I transgenic mice for development of minigene DNA vaccines encoding multiple HLA-restricted CTL epitopes.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: The epitope sequence was imported from the TopBank database and updated in the IEDB.
1st immunogen - Name: KLTPLCVTL
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 1 dose of 100 µg DNA
Immunization - Comments: Mice were pretreated with cardiotoxin 4 to 5 days before immunization with plasmid pMin.1 DNA, containing the epitope and 8 other CTL epitopes, a signal sequence and a Th cell PADRE epitope. Spleens were removed 11 to 14 days after immunization and splenocytes were restimulated in vitro twice with the epitope. In separate experiments, mice were immunized with pMin.1 DNA  with the Th cell PADRE peptide or the signal sequence deleted or the order of the epitopes switched. Mice were immunized at the base of the tail with the epitope and 140 µg  Th epitope, HBV Core 128-140 (TPPAYRPPNAPIL). Spleens were removed 11 to 14 days after immunization and splenocytes were restimulated in vitro with the epitope.
Assay - Comments: CTL from mice immunized with pMin.1 DNA lysed Jurkat A2.1/Kb target cells in the presence of the epitope.  Deletion of the Th cell PADRE peptide or signal sequence from the pMin.1 DNA immunogen reduced the frequency of positive CTL cultures. Switching the positions of two other epitopes in the pMin.1 construct abolished the response to the epitope.

Reference - Authors: G Y Ishioka; J Fikes; G Hermanson; B Livingston; C Crimi; M Qin; M F del Guercio; C Oseroff; C Dahlberg; J Alexander; R W Chesnut; A Sette
Reference - Title: Utilization of MHC class I transgenic mice for development of minigene DNA vaccines encoding multiple HLA-restricted CTL epitopes.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: The epitope sequence was imported from the TopBank database and updated in the IEDB.

Reference - Title: Utilization of MHC class I transgenic mice for development of minigene DNA vaccines encoding multiple HLA-restricted CTL epitopes.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: The epitope sequence was imported from the TopBank database and updated in the IEDB.
1st immunogen - Name: ILKEPVHGV
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 1 dose of 100 µg DNA
Immunization - Comments: Mice were pretreated with cardiotoxin 4 to 5 days before immunization with plasmid pMin.1 DNA, containing the epitope and 8 other CTL epitopes, a signal sequence and a Th cell PADRE epitope. Reference - Authors: Laurence Van Overtvelt; Muriel Andrieu; Valérie Verhasselt; Francine Connan; Jeannine Choppin; Vincent Vercruysse; Michel Goldman; Anne Hosmalin; Bernard Vray
Reference - Title: Trypanosoma cruzi down-regulates lipopolysaccharide-induced MHC class I on human dendritic cells and impairs antigen presentation to specific CD8(+) T lymphocytes.
1st in vivo Process - Process Type: Exposure with existing immune reactivity without evidence for disease
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: The patient was HIV seropositive.
Assay - Comments: The epitope pulsed DC induced the epitope specific CD8 T cell line to produce IFN-g. When DC were infected with T. cruzi or treated with TCM (the supernatant of a parasite suspension, termed as T. cruziconditioned medium), the specific IFN-g release was inhibited up to 39 and 69%, respectively. Addition of soluble CD154, CD152 or an anti-IL-12 antibody during the presentation of the epitope to the epitope specific CD8+ T cell line did not affect IFN-g production, but addition of the blocking anti-MHC class I antibody decreased by 60% IFN-g production.

1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: The details of generating the AGA1 TCR were not described.
Assay - Comments: The crystal structure of the epitope bound to HLA-B*5703 in complex with the AGA1 (Vß19Vα5) TCR was determined by molecular replacement. There is one TCR-peptide-MHC complex per crystallographic asymmetric unit.

Reference - Authors: Guillaume B Stewart-Jones; Peter Simpson; P Anton van der Merwe; Philippa Easterbrook; Andrew J McMichael; Sarah L Rowland-Jones; E Yvonne Jones; Geraldine M Gillespie
Reference - Journal: Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A
Reference - Title: Structural features underlying T-cell receptor sensitivity to concealed MHC class I micropolymorphisms.
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: The details of generating the AGA1 TCR were not described.
Assay - Comments: The affinity of the AGA1 (Vß19Vα5) TCR bound to the epitope/ HLA-B*5703 complex was determined by surface plasmon resonance. The kinetic parameters were: k on = 85000 M/ s and k off = 0.25 s^-1. The binding affinity of AGA1 TCR for epitope/ HLA-B*5703 was approximately five-fold lower than the affinity for epitope/ HLA-B*5701, due to a faster dissociation rate. Mutation Y116S in the HLA-B*5703 heavy chain did not significantly affect the affinity.

Reference - Authors: Guillaume B Stewart-Jones; Peter Simpson; P Anton van der Merwe; Philippa Easterbrook; Andrew J McMichael; Sarah L Rowland-Jones; E Yvonne Jones; Geraldine M Gillespie

Immunization - Comments: The details of generating the AGA1 TCR were not described.
Assay - Comments: The affinity of the AGA1 (Vß19Vα5) TCR bound to the epitope/ HLA-B*5701 complex was determined by surface plasmon resonance. The kinetic parameters were: k on = 83000 M/ s and k off = 0.05 s^-1. The binding affinity of AGA1 TCR for epitope/ HLA-B*5703 was approximately five-fold lower than the affinity for epitope/ HLA-B*5701, due to a faster dissociation rate. Mutation S116Y in the HLA-B*5701 heavy chain, to mimic the sequence of  HLA-B*5703, reduced the affinity almost 10-fold.

Reference - Title: A hairpin turn in a class II MHC-bound peptide orients residues outside the binding groove for T cell recognition.

Immunization - Comments: The CD4+ T cell clone AC-25 was isolated from an individual acutely infected with HIV-1. PBMC were restimulated in vitro with Gag (p24) protein and cloned by limiting dilution.
Assay - Comments: The epitope was the minimal peptide recognized by T cell clone AC-25, in an analysis of truncations of 22-mer peptide AFSPEVIPMFSALSEGATPQDL. The truncated 13-mer peptide PEVIPMFSALSEG binds to HLA-DR1, but does not activate AC-25.

Reference - Journal: Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A
Reference - Title: A hairpin turn in a class II MHC-bound peptide orients residues outside the binding groove for T cell recognition.
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: The CD4+ T cell clone AC-25 was isolated from an individual acutely infected with HIV-1. PBMC were restimulated in vitro with Gag (p24) protein and cloned by limiting dilution.
Assay - Comments: The epitope was recognized by T cell clone AC-25. Alanine scanning of the epitope showed that residues E2, I4, F7 and T15 were critical for T cell recognition. Substitution G13P abolished a reverse turn in the peptide structure and abrogated T cell activation.

Reference - Authors: Jean K Lee; Guillaume Stewart-Jones; Tao Dong; Karl Harlos; Kati Di Gleria; Lucy Dorrell; Daniel C Douek; P Anton van der Merwe; E Yvonne Jones; Andrew J McMichael
Reference - Title: T cell cross-reactivity and conformational changes during TCR engagement.
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: HLA-A2-restricted, HIV-1-specific CTLs were cloned by limiting dilution of PBMCs of infected donors.
Assay - Comments: Two epitope-specific CD8+ T cell clones, that express different T cell receptors, recognized the epitope presented by HLA-A2-positive B cells. The two clones showed similar recognition patterns of the epitope with single amino acid substitutions at every position. Uncloned PBMCs from two other HIV+ donors showed a similar response pattern. Of the 171 variant peptides, less than one-third were recognized with most substitutions at position 1 accepted, and substitutions at positions 3, 4 and 5 the least tolerated.

Reference - Authors: Geraldine M A Gillespie; Guillaume Stewart-Jones; Jaya Rengasamy; Tara Beattie; Job J Bwayo; Francis A Plummer; Rupert Kaul; Andrew J McMichael; Philippa Easterbrook; Tao Dong; E Yvonne Jones; Sarah L Rowland-Jones
Reference - Title: Strong TCR conservation and altered T cell cross-reactivity characterize a B*57-restricted immune response in HIV-1 infection.
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: PBMCs were obtained from a HLA-B*5703-positive HIV-1-infected patient from the progressor Kenyan cohort. The dominant virus present in the patient contained the GAG p24 peptide A2G,S4N (KGFNPEVIPMF). PBMCs were cultured with the A2G,S4N peptide for 12 days. CD8+ T cell clones were also derived.
Assay - Comments: CD8+ T cell lines and clones from a patient in which the dominant virus present contained the GAG p24 peptide A2G,S4N (KGFNPEVIPMF), produced a weak reponse to the epitope after stimulation in vitro with the A2G,S4N or the epitope. The response was much stronger to the A2G,S4N peptide.

Reference - Authors: Geraldine M A Gillespie; Guillaume Stewart-Jones; Jaya Rengasamy; Tara Beattie; Job J Bwayo; Francis A Plummer; Rupert Kaul; Andrew J McMichael; Philippa Easterbrook; Tao Dong; E Yvonne Jones; Sarah L Rowland-Jones
Reference - Title: Strong TCR conservation and altered T cell cross-reactivity characterize a B*57-restricted immune response in HIV-1 infection.
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: PBMCs were obtained from HLA-B*5703-positive HIV-1-infected patients from the progressor Kenyan cohort. PBMCs were cultured with the K11 peptide (KAFSPEVIPMF) for 12 days. CD8+ T cell clones were also derived.
Assay - Comments: CD8+ T cell lines from a patient in which the dominant virus present contained the epitope, showed a dominant response to the epitope after stimulation in vitro with the K11 peptide. CD8+ T cell clones also showed a preferential response to the epitope, as shown by ICS analysis of IFN-gamma secretion.

Reference - Authors: Geraldine M A Gillespie; Guillaume Stewart-Jones; Jaya Rengasamy; Tara Beattie; Job J Bwayo; Francis A Plummer; Rupert Kaul; Andrew J McMichael; Philippa Easterbrook; Tao Dong; E Yvonne Jones; Sarah L Rowland-Jones
Reference - Title: Strong TCR conservation and altered T cell cross-reactivity characterize a B*57-restricted immune response in HIV-1 infection.
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: PBMCs were obtained from HLA-B*5703-positive HIV-1-infected patients from the progressor Kenyan cohort. PBMCs were cultured with the K11 peptide (KAFSPEVIPMF) for 12 days. CD8+ T cell clones were also derived.
Assay - Comments: The epitope-specific CD8+ T cell clone from a patient in which the dominant virus present contained the epitope, showed a weaker response to the K11 peptide after stimulation in vitro with the K11 peptide.

Reference - Authors: Rachid Boucherma; Hédia Kridane-Miledi; Romain Bouziat; Michael Rasmussen; Tanja Gatard; Francina Langa-Vives; Brigitte Lemercier; Annick Lim; Marion Bérard; Lbachir Benmohamed; Søren Buus; Ronald Rooke; François A Lemonnier
Reference - Title: HLA-A*01:03, HLA-A*24:02, HLA-B*08:01, HLA-B*27:05, HLA-B*35:01, HLA-B*44:02, and HLA-C*07:01 monochain transgenic/H-2 class I null mice: novel versatile preclinical models of human T cell responses.
1st immunogen - Name: RYLKDQQLL
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 100 ug peptide and 140 ug H-2 IAb– restricted HBV core 128–140 helper peptide (TPPAYRPPNAPIL) coemulsified
Immunization - Comments: C57BL/6 transgenic mice expressing HLA-A*01:03, -A*24:02, -B*08:01, -B*27:05, -B*35:01, -B*44:01, or -C*07:01 as chimeric monochain molecules were generated and immunized.
Assay - Comments: Similar results were found when immunization was performed with a DNA plasmid vector encoding a recombinant HBV glycoprotein in which the pre-S2 coding segment was replaced by the nucleotide sequence of the epitope.

Reference - Authors: Erik Martinez-Hackert; Nadia Anikeeva; Spyros A Kalams; Bruce D Walker; Wayne A Hendrickson; Yuri Sykulev
Reference - Title: Structural basis for degenerate recognition of natural HIV peptide variants by cytotoxic lymphocytes.
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: Generation of the T Cell clone was previously described in the cited reference: Brander et al. (1998) J Clin Investig 101: 2559-1566 [PMID: 9616277].
Assay - Comments: The epitope-specific CTL D3 lysed JY-B cells pulsed with the natural variant peptides SL9-8V (SLYNTVAVL), SL9-3F (SLFNTVATL), SL9-5S (SLYNSVATL), and more weakly to SL9-6I (SLYNTIATL) pulsed targets. CTL D3 also weakly recognized synthetic peptide SL9-4Q (SLYQTVATL), but not synthetic peptides SL9-4A (SLYATVATL) or SL9-3A (SLANTVATL).

Reference - Title: Conflicting selective forces affect T cell receptor contacts in an immunodominant human immunodeficiency virus epitope.
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: The T cell clone was generated from PBMCs obtained from an HIV-infected HLA-A*02-positive patient. Clone G-10 from one patient was selected with peptides SLYNTVATL and SLFNTVATL. The TCR was cloned and the soluble form was expressed.
Assay - Comments: The affinity of the G-10 TCR for the epitope/HLA-A2 complex was determined by surface plasmon resonance. The kinetic parameters were: k on = 32,000 M^-1 s^-1 and k off = 0.05 s^-1.

Reference - Title: Targeting of antigen to the herpesvirus entry mediator augments primary adaptive immune responses.
1st immunogen - Name: gag protein
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 1 dose of 1 x 10E10 virus particles
Immunization - Comments: Mice were immunized with chimeric protein containing a truncated form of HIV-1 Gag  inserted after amino acid 288 of gD. The gD-antigen chimeric genes were inserted into DNA vaccines or  E1-deleted, chimpanzee-derived adenovirus serotype 68 (AdC68) vectors.
Assay - Comments: Higher reactivity was seen when the mice were immunized with the AdC68 vector.

Reference - Title: Antigen processing influences HIV-specific cytotoxic T lymphocyte immunodominance.
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: PBMCs were obtained from HLA-B*2705-positive chronically HIV-1-infected patients. PBMCs were stimulated in vitro with the epitope, the truncated peptide KRWIILGL, or a longer 15mer, 17mer or 19mer peptide containing the epitope to generate cell lines.
Assay - Comments: T cell lines derived from PBMCs stimulated in vitro with the epitope, the truncated peptide KRWIILGL, or a longer 15mer, 17mer or 19mer peptide containing the epitope showed a maximal response to the epitope even compared to the original stimulating peptide. Clones showing higher responses to the longer peptides, that represent proteasomal precursors,  could be selected.

1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)

Reference - Title: Structure of TCR and antigen complexes at an immunodominant CTL epitope in HIV-1 infection.
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: Generation of the T Cell clone was previously described in the cited reference: Kawana-Tachikawa et al. (2002) J Virol 76(23): 11982-11988 [PMID: 12414940]. PBMCs from HLA-A*2402-positive HIV-1-infected individuals were cultured with autologous phytohemagglutinin-stimulated irradiated PBMCs pulsed with the epitope. Clones were obtained by limiting dilution and the H27-14 TCR was cloned and expressed.
Assay - Location of Assay Data in Refere: Figures 3, 4, Supplementary Figures 3, 4, 5, Supplementary Table S2, S4, S5 and PDB 3VXR
Assay - Comments: The crystal structure of the epitope/ HLA-A*2402 complex bound by the H27-14 TCR was determined by molecular replacement.  The complex crystallized in space group C21.

Immunization - Comments: PBMCs were obtained from healthy, HIV-1 and HIV-2-uninfected participants in the HIV-CORE 002 trial who received the conserved immunogen HIVconsv. Short-term cell lines were derived from frozen PBMC taken at week 28. The PBMCs were expanded by using pools 1 to 6 of HIVconsv-derived 15-mer peptides overlapping by 11 amino acids for 10 days.
Assay - Comments: PBMCs from vaccinated subjects were tested for epitope-specific IFNg production.

Reference - Title: HIV-1-Specific CD8 T Cells Exhibit Limited Cross-Reactivity during Acute Infection.
1st immunogen - Name: HIV-1 M:B
Immunization - Comments: PBMCs and plasma samples were obtained from 11 patients acutely infected (median of 31 d after the estimated date of infection; range, 16–60 d) with HIV-1 clade B. Acute infection was diagnosed at the first screening visit by detectable HIV-1 viral RNA in plasma and a lack of HIV-specific Abs on Western blot. Transmitted founder virus (TFV) sequences were inferred from the plasma of these 11 patients at Fiebig stage III or earlier using a single genome amplification method.
Assay - Comments: CD8+ T cells responded to the epitope.

Reference - Authors: Victor Y Du; Anju Bansal; Jonathan Carlson; Jesus F Salazar-Gonzalez; Maria G Salazar; Kristin Ladell; Stephanie Gras; Tracy M Josephs; Sonya L Heath; David A Price; Jamie Rossjohn; Eric Hunter; Paul A Goepfert

1st immunogen - Name: HIV-1 M:B
Immunization - Comments: PBMCs and plasma samples were obtained from 11 patients acutely infected (median of 31 d after the estimated date of infection; range, 16–60 d) with HIV-1 clade B. Acute infection was diagnosed at the first screening visit by detectable HIV-1 viral RNA in plasma and a lack of HIV-specific Abs on Western blot. Transmitted founder virus (TFV) sequences were inferred from the plasma of these 11 patients at Fiebig stage III or earlier using a single genome amplification method. CD8+ T cells were stimulated in vitro with RL10-pulsed monocytes.
Assay - Comments: RL10-specific CD8+ T cells responded to the variant epitope.

Reference - Title: Antiviral CD8<sup>+</sup> T Cells Restricted by Human Leukocyte Antigen Class II Exist during Natural HIV Infection and Exhibit Clonal Expansion.
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: Purified CD8+ T cells were isolated from the peripheral blood mononuclear cells (PBMCs) of a subject with untreated HIV-1 infection, who maintained viral loads of less than 2,000 RNA copies/mL plasma. The CD8+ T cells were co-cultured with mouse lymphoblastoid cell lines (LCL) stably expressing a single recombinant human DRB1 molecule matched to the donor.
Assay - Comments: CD8+ T cells from an HIV controller, subject 474723, produced IFN-γ in response to the peptide 41, (YVDRFYKTLRAEQASQEV) containing the epitope, presented by class II HLA DRB1*11:01 in an assay of 66 overlapping peptides spanning the sequence of HIV Gag protein. The restriction of the response was confirmed by showing it was blocked with anti-HLA-DR antibody. N- and C-terminal truncations showed that the maximum response was to the epitope and the core sequence was probably FYKTLRAEQA.

Immunization - Comments: Purified CD8+ T cells were isolated from the peripheral blood mononuclear cells (PBMCs) of a subjects (n = 129) with untreated HIV-1 infection, of whom 101 controllers maintained viral loads of less than 2,000 RNA copies/mL plasma.
Assay - Comments: CD8+ T cells from an HIV controller, subject 474723, were stained with epitope/HLA-DR11 tetramers. The response to the epitope was a dominant response. The TCR sequence from single cells was determined.

Immunization - Comments: Peripheral blood mononuclear cells (PBMCs) were obtained from a subject with untreated HIV-1 infection (HIV controller, subject 474723), who maintained viral loads of less than 2,000 RNA copies/mL plasma. Cells were stained with epitope/HLA-DRB1*11:01 tetramers and CD8+ tetramer+ T cells were single cell-sorted and the TCRs isolated. TCR-negative mouse hybridomas were transduced with either TRAV6 with TRBV2 or TRAV26 with TRBV2 epitope-specific TCR chains.

Epitope-specific TCR hybridoma TRAV6 with TRBV2, but not TRAV26 with TRVB2, produced IL-2 in a dose-dependent manner in response to the Gag41 peptide containing the epitope.

1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: Generation of the T Cell clone was previously described in the cited reference: Kawana-Tachikawa et al. (2002) J Virol 76(23): 11982-11988 [PMID: 12414940]. PBMCs from HLA-A*2402-positive HIV-1-infected individuals were cultured with autologous phytohemagglutinin-stimulated irradiated PBMCs pulsed with the epitope. Clones were obtained by limiting dilution and the T36-5 TCR was cloned and expressed.
Assay - Comments: The affinity of the T36-5 TCR for binding to the epitope/ HLA-A*2402 complex was determined by surface plasmon resonance.

Reference - Authors: Chao-Ying Zhou; Rui-Ning Wang; Qian Wen; Wen-Ting He; Shi-Meng Zhang; Xia-Lin Du; Jia-Hui Yang; Li Ma
Reference - Title: Alanine Mutagenesis in the Complementarity Determining Region 3 of the MTB and HIV-1 Peptide-Bispecific T Cell Receptor Beta Chain Affects Ligand Recognition.
Immunization - Comments: A bispecific TCR was screened out from peripheral blood mononuclear cells from a HLA-A*0201+ healthy individual using CDR3 spectratype analysis as described in the cited reference: Zhou et al. (2016) J Cell Mol Med 20:1984–1998 [PMID: 27113787]. The TCR recognizes both the epitope MTB Ag85B(199-207) and HIV-1 Env(120-128). The TCR α17 and ß15 genes were cloned into a lentivirus expression vector. The bispecific TCR was mutated at each position in the CDR3ß sequence DGTAS (114-118) to generate the mutant receptor with substitution D114A, G115A, T116A, A117G, or S118A. The wild type or mutant TCR receptor were transduced into CD8+ T cells.
Assay - Comments: The CD8+ T cells transduced with the bispecific TCR were stained with epitope/HLA-A*0201 dextramers as well as Ag85B(199-207)/HLA-A*0201 dextramers. The CD8+ T cells transduced with the bispecific mutant TCR G115A, T116A, or A117G, but not D114A or S118A, were stained with epitope/HLA-A*0201 dextramers as well as Ag85B(199-207)/HLA-A*0201 dextramers.
Effector Cell - TCR Name: bispecific TCR, bispecific TCR G115A, bispecific TCR T116A, bispecific TCR A117G

Reference - Authors: Chao-Ying Zhou; Rui-Ning Wang; Qian Wen; Wen-Ting He; Shi-Meng Zhang; Xia-Lin Du; Jia-Hui Yang; Li Ma
Reference - Title: Alanine Mutagenesis in the Complementarity Determining Region 3 of the MTB and HIV-1 Peptide-Bispecific T Cell Receptor Beta Chain Affects Ligand Recognition.
Immunization - Comments: A bispecific TCR was screened out from peripheral blood mononuclear cells from a HLA-A*0201+ healthy individual using CDR3 spectratype analysis as described in the cited reference: Zhou et al. (2016) J Cell Mol Med 20:1984–1998 [PMID: 27113787]. The TCR recognizes both the epitope MTB Ag85B(199-207) and HIV-1 Env(120-128). The TCR α17 and ß15 genes were cloned into a lentivirus expression vector. The bispecific TCR was mutated at each position in the CDR3ß sequence DGTAS (114-118) to generate the mutant receptor with substitution D114A, G115A, T116A, A117G, or S118A. The wild type or mutant TCR receptor were transduced into CD8+ T cells.
Assay - Comments: The CD8+ T cells transduced with the bispecific TCR produced cytokine in response to the epitope presented by T2 cells expressing HLA-A*0201, as well as to the Ag85B(199-207) peptide. The CD8+ T cells transduced with the bispecific mutant TCR G115A, T116A, or A117G, but not D114A or S118A, produced cytokine in response to the epitope presented by T2 cells expressing HLA-A*0201, as well as to the Ag85B(199-207) peptide. ICS gave similar results.

Reference - Authors: Madhura Mukhopadhyay; Moran Galperin; Mandar Patgaonkar; Sandhya Vasan; David D Ho; Alexandre Nouël; Mathieu Claireaux; Daniela Benati; Olivier Lambotte; Yaoxing Huang; Lisa A Chakrabarti
Reference - Title: DNA Vaccination by Electroporation Amplifies Broadly Cross-Restricted Public TCR Clonotypes Shared with HIV Controllers.
1st immunogen - Name: Gag-Pol polyprotein
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 3 doses of 4 mg ADVAX DNA administered at weeks 0, 8, and 36
Immunization - Comments: Healthy volunteers were vaccinated with ADVAX by electroporation (EP) or by intramuscular injection. Among participants in the EP groups (n = 24), those in the EP high-dose group (n = 8) received 4 mg of ADVAX DNA administered at weeks 0, 8, and 36 via the TriGrid device (Ichor Medical System). Participants in the i.m. group (n = 8) received 4 mg of ADVAX DNA at weeks 0 and 8 via syringe i.m. injection. Participants in the placebo group received saline via EP at weeks 0 and 8 (n = 5) or weeks 0, 8, and 36 (n = 3). Cryopreserved PBMCs from vaccinated volunteers were thawed, stimulated with the epitope, and propagated as short-term primary CD4+ T cell lines.
Assay - Comments: CD4+ T cell lines from healthy volunteers vaccinated with ADVAX by electroporation responded to the epitope; 4 of 7 positive at week 10 and 4 of 5 positive at week 38. Volunteers vaccinated by intramuscular injection did not respond.

Assay - Comments: CD4+ T cell lines from healthy volunteers vaccinated with ADVAX by electroporation responded to the epitope, but infrequently. Responses did not differ significantly between CD4+ T cell lines obtained from volunteers vaccinated by  EP versus intramuscular injection.

Immunization - Comments: Samples were obtained from HIV-infected patients. The HIV controller (HIC) group was defined as HIV-1–infected patients who had been seropositive for >5 y, had received no antiretroviral treatment, and for whom >90% of plasma viral load measurements were undetectable by standard assays. The treated patients (highly active antiretroviral therapy [HAART] group; n = 14) had received antiretroviral therapy for a minimum of 5 y and showed efficient HIV-1 suppression with viral loads

The AS1 or AS7 TCR was cloned and transduced in the J76 cell line, which is a Jurkat derivative lacking endogenous TCR expression.

The AS1- or AS7-J76 cell line did not respond to APC expressing DR3, DR4 or DR7.

Reference - Authors: Madhura Mukhopadhyay; Moran Galperin; Mandar Patgaonkar; Sandhya Vasan; David D Ho; Alexandre Nouël; Mathieu Claireaux; Daniela Benati; Olivier Lambotte; Yaoxing Huang; Lisa A Chakrabarti
Reference - Title: DNA Vaccination by Electroporation Amplifies Broadly Cross-Restricted Public TCR Clonotypes Shared with HIV Controllers.
1st immunogen - Name: Gag-Pol polyprotein
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 3 doses of 4 mg ADVAX DNA administered at weeks 0, 8, and 36
Immunization - Comments: Healthy volunteers were vaccinated with ADVAX by electroporation (EP) or by intramuscular injection. Among participants in the EP groups (n = 24), those in the EP high-dose group (n = 8) received 4 mg of ADVAX DNA administered at weeks 0, 8, and 36 via the TriGrid device (Ichor Medical System). Participants in the i.m. group (n = 8) received 4 mg of ADVAX DNA at weeks 0 and 8 via syringe i.m. injection. Participants in the placebo group received saline via EP at weeks 0 and 8 (n = 5) or weeks 0, 8, and 36 (n = 3). Cryopreserved PBMCs from vaccinated volunteers were thawed, stimulated with the epitope, and propagated as short-term primary CD4+ T cell lines. The AS1 or AS7 TCR was cloned and transduced in the J76 cell line, which is a Jurkat derivative lacking endogenous TCR expression.
Assay - Comments: The J76 cell line transduced with the epitope-specific AS1 or AS7 TCR was activated by the epitope presented by mouse L cell transfected to express a single HLA-DR allele (DR1, DR11, DR15 or DRB5), as analyzed by increased CD69 surface expression. The AS1- or AS7-J76 cell line did not respond to APC expressing DR3, DR4 or DR7.

Reference - Authors: David K Cole; Anna Fuller; Garry Dolton; Efthalia Zervoudi; Mateusz Legut; Kim Miles; Lori Blanchfield; Florian Madura; Christopher J Holland; Anna M Bulek; John S Bridgeman; John J Miles; Andrea J A Schauenburg; Konrad Beck; Brian D Evavold; Pierre J Rizkallah; Andrew K Sewell
Reference - Title: Dual Molecular Mechanisms Govern Escape at Immunodominant HLA A2-Restricted HIV Epitope.
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: Generation of the T Cell clone 868 was previously described in the cited references: Sewell et al. (1997) Eur J Immunol 27:2323–9 [PMID: 9341776] and Varela-Rohena et al. (2008) Nature Med 14(12):1390-5 [PMID: 18997777]. Patient 9300868 (A2/24, B27/35), a HIV-1 infected homosexual male was first diagnosed as HIV-positive in 1993 but the duration of  his infection is unknown. He made a vigorous CTL response to the HLA-A2-restricted p17-8 epitope SLYNTVATL of  p17 Gag. Blood  taken in April 1996 was used to grow out a line of cells (CTL 868 line) which killed autologous peptide-pulsed B cell targets. Repeated attempts to generate SL9-specific T-cell clones from the 868 line by limiting dilution were unsuccessful. Therefore, phage display was used to isolate a TCR from a T-cell line that was only ~14% tetramer positive for the SL9 antigen. Flow cytometry of the starting CTL line confirmed that all SL9-tetramer+ cells in this line expressed a TCR made from the same combination of variable genes as the TCR selected from the phage library. The 868 TCR α and ß chains were expressed and purified.
Assay - Comments: The crystal structure of the epitope/HLA-A2 complex bound by the 868 TCR was determined, solved by molecular replacement.

1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: Generation of the T cell clone was previously described in the cited reference: Kawana-Tachikawa et al. (2002) J Virol 76:11 982–11988 [PMID: 12414940]. The S19-2 CTL clone was established from peripheral blood mononuclear cells (PBMCs) of an HIV-1-infected individual carrying HLA-A*24:02. PBMCs were cultured for 2 weeks with autologous irradiated PHA-stimulated PBMCs pulsed with Nef138-10 and with added interleukin-2 and an anti-CD28 MAb. The cells were further stimulated with irradiated autologous B-LCLs pulsed with peptides for another 7 to 10 days.
Assay - Comments: The crystal structure of the epitope/HLA-A*24:02 complex bound by the S19-2 TCR was determined.

Reference - Title: Effects of Cross-Presentation, Antigen Processing, and Peptide Binding in HIV Evasion of T Cell Immunity.
1st immunogen - Name: Envelope glycoprotein gp160 precursor
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 3 doses of 100 µg of gp120MN at 2-week intervals
Immunization - Comments: Mice were immunized i.p. three times at 2-wk intervals with experimental vaccines containing 100 μg of WT gp120MN or the mutant VV gp120MN formulated with CAF09 consisting of dimethyldioctadecylammonium bromide, synthetic monomycoloyl glycerol analog MMG-1, and the TLR-3 agonist polyinosinic-polycytidylic acid by the film method. Fourteen days after the final immunization, splenocytes were isolated and stimulated in vitro with the epitope.
Assay - Comments: Mice immunized with the mutant VV gp120 protein displayed a greater response to the epitope than animals given the WT gp120 protein. The VV gp120 protein is mutated at T322 T323 to V322 V323 at a cathepsin S cleavage site in the V3 loop.

Reference - Title: Effects of Cross-Presentation, Antigen Processing, and Peptide Binding in HIV Evasion of T Cell Immunity.
1st immunogen - Name: Envelope glycoprotein gp160 precursor
1st immunogen - Dose Schedule: 3 doses of 100 µg of gp120MN at 2-week intervals

1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)

Reference - Authors: Brenna C Simons; Scott E Vancompernolle; Rita M Smith; Jie Wei; Louise Barnett; Shelly L Lorey; Dirk Meyer-Olson; Spyros A Kalams
Reference - Title: Despite biased TRBV gene usage against a dominant HLA B57-restricted epitope, TCR diversity can provide recognition of circulating epitope variants.
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: PBMCs were obtained from nine chronically HIV-infected, HLA-B57+ subjects. CD8+T cells were stained with epitope/HLA-B57 teramers and sorted. In parallel, an equivalent number of KF11 tetramer-depleted CD8+ T cells were sorted and also subjected to TCR sequence analysis.
Assay - Comments: The epitope-speciﬁc TCR clonotypes of the KF11/HLA-B57+ CD8+ T cells were analyzed.

Reference - Authors: Brenna C Simons; Scott E Vancompernolle; Rita M Smith; Jie Wei; Louise Barnett; Shelly L Lorey; Dirk Meyer-Olson; Spyros A Kalams
Reference - Title: Despite biased TRBV gene usage against a dominant HLA B57-restricted epitope, TCR diversity can provide recognition of circulating epitope variants.
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: Subjects with expression of the HLA B57 allele were identified from a cohort of 146 therapy-naive HIV+ subjects. Nine subjects that responded to the peptide KF11 (KAFSPEVIPMF) were evaluated. Two subjects harbored a K162R mutation found in the epitope.
Assay - Comments: The magnitude of the responses to KF11 consensus peptide in subjects tended to be equal or higher than that of responses directed against the K162R variant epitope.

Reference - Title: Identification of Native and Posttranslationally Modified HLA-B*57:01-Restricted HIV Envelope Derived Epitopes Using Immunoproteomics.
Epitope - Epitope Comments: The epitope modification is Trp->Kynurenin(W)@10.
Immunization - Comments: PBMCs were obtained from healthy donors expressing HLA-B*57:01. PBMCs were stimulated epitope-pulsed irradiated autologous APCS and cultured for 13 days.
Assay - Comments: T cells from one of 5 donors were activated by the epitope, as assessed by their dual production of IFN-γ and TNF-α.

Reference - Title: CD4<sup>+</sup> T cell-mediated HLA class II cross-restriction in HIV controllers.
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: Generation of the F24 T cell clone was previously described in the cited reference: Benati et al. (2016) J Clin Invest 126(6):2093-2108 [PMID: 27111229]. Samples were obtained from HIV-infected patients. The HIV controller (HIC) group was defined as HIV-1–infected patients who had been seropositive for >5 y, had received no antiretroviral treatment, and for whom >90% of plasma viral load measurements were undetectable by standard assays. PBMCs from patients were stimulated with peptide Gag293, and propagated as short-term primary CD4+ T cell lines. The F24 TCR was cloned and purified.
Assay - Location of Assay Data in Refere: Figure 5, 6, S10, S11, Tables S3, S4 and PDB 6CQL
Assay - Comments: The crystal structure of the epitope/DRB1*11:01 complex bound by the F24 TCR was determined.

Immunization - Comments: Generation of the F24 T cell clone was previously described in the cited reference: Benati et al. (2016) J Clin Invest 126(6):2093-2108 [PMID: 27111229]. Samples were obtained from HIV-infected patients. The HIV controller (HIC) group was defined as HIV-1–infected patients who had been seropositive for >5 y, had received no antiretroviral treatment, and for whom >90% of plasma viral load measurements were undetectable by standard assays. PBMCs from patients were stimulated with peptide Gag293, and propagated as short-term primary CD4+ T cell lines. The F24 TCR was cloned and purified.
Assay - Location of Assay Data in Refere: Tables 1, S8, S9, Figures S2 and S12
Assay - Comments: The affinity measurements of the TCR-pMHC interaction were determined by surface plasmon resonance.  Alanine substitutions of HLA-DR11 residues contacted by the TCR did not decrease the affinity. Mutations E55A or A68L in the HLA-DRα chain decreased the affinity > 5-fold. Alanine substitution of residues in the F24 TCR α or ß chain that contacted the epitope-DR complex reduced the affinity >5-fold.

1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: Generation of the F24 T cell clone was previously described in the cited reference: Benati et al. (2016) J Clin Invest 126(6):2093-2108 [PMID: 27111229]. Samples were obtained from HIV-infected patients. The HIV controller (HIC) group was defined as HIV-1–infected patients who had been seropositive for >5 y, had received no antiretroviral treatment, and for whom >90% of plasma viral load measurements were undetectable by standard assays. PBMCs from patients were stimulated with the epitope, and propagated as short-term primary CD4+ T cell lines. The F24 TCR was cloned and transduced in the J76 cell line, which is a Jurkat derivative lacking endogenous TCR expression.
Assay - Comments: TCR-expressing CFSE–labeled J76 T cells and Gag293-pulsed antigen-presenting cells (APCs) expressing HLA-DR1, HLA-DR11, or HLA-DR15/DRB5 formed conjugates, as evaluated by counting the percentage of double positive CFSE+–HLA-DR+ events by flow cytometry. No conjugates were detected with HLA-DR7 APCs.

Immunization - Comments: Generation of the F24 T cell clone was previously described in the cited reference: Benati et al. (2016) J Clin Invest 126(6):2093-2108 [PMID: 27111229]. Samples were obtained from HIV-infected patients. The HIV controller (HIC) group was defined as HIV-1–infected patients who had been seropositive for >5 y, had received no antiretroviral treatment, and for whom >90% of plasma viral load measurements were undetectable by standard assays. PBMCs from patients were stimulated with the epitope, and propagated as short-term primary CD4+ T cell lines. The F24 TCR was cloned and transduced in the J76 cell line, which is a Jurkat derivative lacking endogenous TCR expression.
Assay - Comments: The epitope was shown to be the minimal core epitope of the Gag293 peptide (FRDYVDRFYKTLRAEQASQE) to activate TCR-expressing J76 T cells when presented by APCs expressing HLA-DR11. Alanine substitution of the RQ13 peptide at position 2, 4, 7, 9 or 10 reduced or abrogated the response of TCR-expressing J76 T cells.

Reference - Authors: M C Gagliardi; G De Petrillo; S Salemi; L Boffa; M G Longobardi; P Dellabona; G Casorati; N Tanigaki; R Harris; A Lanzavecchia
Reference - Title: Presentation of peptides by cultured monocytes or activated T cells allows specific priming of human cytotoxic T lymphocytes in vitro.
Assay - Comments: A positive response was observed when monocytes or activated T cell clones were used as a source of peptide-pulsed APCs for in vitro stimulation. No response was observed when PBMC, T2 cells, or EBV-B cells were used as APCs for in vitro stimulation. The optimal timing for peptide loading on monocytes coincides with the first 4 hours of in vitro culture when there is a maximum increase of surface class I molecules. When a huB7.1-lgM chimeric protein or an IgM anti-CD28 mAb was added to unseparated PBMC and peptide, a clear CTL response was detected. These results demonstrate that co-stimulation via CD28 is sufficient for the induction o f the CTL response and suggest that peptide presentation on frequent non-professional APC present among PBMC (resting T and B cells expressing class I but not co-stimulatory molecules) may induce peptide-specific anergy in CTL precursors. The response was not dependant on B7.1 or CTLA-4 co-stimulatory signals, or on CD45RO+ memory cells.

Reference - Authors: Alok V Joglekar; Michael T Leonard; John D Jeppson; Margaret Swift; Guideng Li; Stephanie Wong; Songming Peng; Jesse M Zaretsky; James R Heath; Antoni Ribas; Michael T Bethune; David Baltimore
Reference - Title: T cell antigen discovery via signaling and antigen-presenting bifunctional receptors.
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: Generation of the T Cell clone EC27 was previously described in [PMID:29437954]. Sequences for the epitope specific TCR were cloned in the pCCLc-MND-X backbone and expressed in Jurkat cells.
Assay - Comments: Jurkat cells expressing epitope specific TCRs bound to Jurkat cells expressing the epitope in a chimeric signaling and antigen-presenting bifunctional receptor (SABR). SABRs present an extracellular complex comprising an epitope and major histocompatibility complex (MHC), and induce intracellular signaling via a TCR-like signal after binding with a cognate TCR. Activation was measured by GFP expression and CD69 upregulation. The epitope was also enriched using a SABR library.

Reference - Authors: Andreas Moritz; Raghavendra Anjanappa; Claudia Wagner; Sebastian Bunk; Martin Hofmann; Gabriele Pszolla; Ankur Saikia; Maria Garcia-Alai; Rob Meijers; Hans-Georg Rammensee; Sebastian Springer; Dominik Maurer
Reference - Title: High-throughput peptide-MHC complex generation and kinetic screenings of TCRs with peptide-receptive HLA-A*02:01 molecules.
1st immunogen - Name: Human immunodeficiency virus 1 (human immunodeficiency virus 1 HIV-1)
Immunization - Comments: Generation of the parent T cell line 868 was previously described in the references: Sewell et al. (1997) [PMID: 9341776] and Varela-Rohena et al. (2008) [PMID: 18997777]. An HIV-1 infected  male patient made a vigorous CTL response to the HLA-A2-restricted p17-8 epitope SLYNTVATL of p17 Gag. The 868 TCR α and ß chains were cloned. An affinity-matured TCR 868Z11 was converted to a single-chain TCR (scTv) as described in Aggen et al. (2011) [PMID: 21159619]. bsTCR bs-868Z11-CD3 is linked to a humanized anti-CD3 antibody functioning as T cell-engaging domain.
Assay - Comments: The binding affinities of bs-868Z11-CD3 for DS-A*02:01 SL9 and WT-A*02:01 SL9 pMHCs were similar.

Reference - Authors: Chao-Ying Zhou; Rui-Ning Wang; Wen-Ting He; Dong-Rong Luo; Si-Rui Yuan; Qian Wen; Sheng-Feng Hu; Xin-Ying Zhou; Li Ma
Reference - Title: Functional analysis of the antigen binding sites on the MTB/HIV-1 peptide bispecific T-cell receptor complementarity determining region 3α.
Immunization - Comments: Generation of MTB Ag85B(199-207) and HIV-1 Env(120-128) bi-specific T cells was published in the cited reference Zhou et al., Front Immunol 2017; 8:983 [PMID: 28861087]. PBMCs were collected from healthy donors and stimulated with autologous monocyte-derived dendritic cells loaded with the epitope. CD8+ T cells were sorted. The TCR α17 and ß15 chains carrying the AV17 and BV15 CD3 spectratypes were singly enriched and combined.  The TCR genes were cloned into retroviral vectors to create bi-specific TCR genes used for transduction into CD8+ T cells.
Assay - Comments: The bi-specific CD8+ T cells reacted with the epitope-specific dextramer.

Reference - Title: Simultaneous analysis of pMHC binding and reactivity unveils virus-specific CD8 T cell immunity to a concise epitope set.

Reference - Authors: Haotian Du; Leena Mallik; Daniel Hwang; Yi Sun; Chengzi Kaku; Daniel Hoces; Shirley M Sun; Reem Ghinnagow; Stephen D Carro; Hoang Anh T Phan; Sagar Gupta; Wyatt Blackson; Hyejin Lee; Christian A Choe; Devin Dersh; Jingjia Liu; Braxton Bell; Hongli Yang; Georgia F Papadaki; Michael C Young; Emily Zhou; Gina El Nesr; Kimia Dasteh Goli; Laurence C Eisenlohr; Andy J Minn; Rogelio A Hernandez-Lopez; Joseph G Jardine; Nikolaos G Sgourakis; Po-Ssu Huang
Reference - Title: Targeting peptide antigens using a multiallelic MHC I-binding system.
Immunization - Comments: The pMHC binding molecule TRACeR-I was based on the pMHC II-binding platform, TRACeR-II [PMID: 39672953]. The TRACeR-II scaffold was mutated to create an interface to engage MHC I antigens through combinatorial library screening. A TRACeR-I was selected against the HLA-A*24:02/HIV Nef target.
Assay - Comments: TRACeR-I HLA-A*24:02/HIV Nef bound specifically to its target and did not cross-react with other peptide MHC complexes tested.

Reference - Title: Targeting peptide antigens using a multiallelic MHC I-binding system.
Immunization - Comments: The pMHC binding molecule TRACeR-I was based on the pMHC II-binding platform, TRACeR-II [PMID: 39672953]. The TRACeR-II scaffold was mutated to create an interface to engage MHC I antigens through combinatorial library screening. A TRACeR-I was selected against the HLA-A*24:02/HIV Nef target.
